  </div>
</section>

<section class="card" aria-label="How climate-based garden planning works">
  <div class="cardHead">
    <h2>How climate-based garden planning works in short seasons</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      Most gardening advice assumes a long, forgiving growing season. In cold or short-season climates, that assumption breaks down.
    </p>
  </div>

  <p>
    Planting calendars offer general timing guidelines, but they don’t account for local frost patterns or heat accumulation.
    In many regions, the difference between success and failure comes down to two measurable constraints:
    when frost typically leaves in spring and returns in fall — and how much accumulated heat your season delivers in between.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is why <strong>frost dates and growing degree days (GDD)</strong> must be considered together.
    Frost defines your seasonal boundary. GDD determines whether a crop has enough heat to mature inside that boundary.
    We explain this integrated approach in more detail in
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">
      How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together
    </a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    Many gardeners rely on “days to maturity” printed on seed packets.
    But in cold climates, that number alone can be misleading.
    It assumes sufficient heat accumulation — something that isn’t guaranteed in shorter or cooler seasons.
    Our guide on
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">
      Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates
    </a>
    explains why this matters.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you’re planning in a genuinely short growing season, the key is not just timing — it’s margin.
    Your plan should work in a typical year, not just in an unusually warm one.
    For a complete system-level framework, see
    <a href="/guides/how-to-plan-a-garden-in-a-short-growing-season/">
      How to Plan a Garden in a Short Growing Season
    </a>.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    The goal isn’t perfect prediction. It’s building a climate-aware plan that fits your actual season.
  </p>
</section>